Breadth First Search: A Complete Guide

Understanding how BFS explores graphs level by level to find the shortest path

Imagine you're standing at the center of a maze and want to find the shortest way out. Instead of wandering down one path until you hit a dead end, you could explore all nearby exits first, then all the exits one step farther, and so on. This is the essence of breadth-first search (BFS)â€”a systematic graph traversal algorithm that explores nodes layer by layer. BFS visits all neighbors at the current distance before moving to nodes that are farther away. This level-by-level exploration ensures that when you first reach a destination node in an unweighted graph, you've found the shortest path to it.

Breadth-First Search relies on a queue data structure to explore a graph systematically, layer by layer. The algorithm begins by placing the starting node into a queue and marking it as visited. Then, in each iteration, BFS removes (dequeues) the node at the front of the queue, processes it, and adds (enqueues) all of its unvisited neighbors to the back of the queue. This first-in, first-out (FIFO) behavior of the queue ensures that nodes are explored in order of their distance from the startâ€”completing one entire level before moving to the next. By marking nodes as visited when they're enqueued, BFS avoids revisiting nodes and prevents infinite loops in graphs with cycles.
